        <article class="example-article">
            <h2 class="example-title">iA Writer: Content-First Design</h2>
            
            <blockquote class="example-quote">
                <p>"The best interface is no interface. The best tool gets out of the way and lets you focus on what matters."</p>
                <footer>— Information Architects</footer>
            </blockquote>
            
            <figure class="example-figure">
                <img src="{{ '/images/examples/ia-writer-minimal.jpg' | baseUrl }}"
                     alt="iA Writer's minimal interface highlighting constrained line length and comfortable typography."
                     loading="lazy"
                     class="example-screenshot">
                <figcaption class="image-caption">Visual: The pure focus on typography and optimal measure (65-75 CPL) is the ultimate demonstration of content-first HM.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            
            <p>
                iA Writer stands as a canonical example of Humanist Modernism in digital product design. The application strips away decorative elements and geometric distractions, placing the reader's experience at the absolute center of its design philosophy.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Optimal Reading Measure</h3>
            <p>
                The text editor constrains the writing area to approximately 65-75 characters per line—the scientifically proven optimal width for reading comfort. This constraint is not a limitation but a liberation: it forces writers to consider their audience's visual comfort and cognitive load. Each character is deliberately positioned within a generous, readable measure, echoing Edward Tufte's insistence that clarity serves the reader first.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Typography as Content</h3>
            <p>
                iA Writer uses carefully selected typefaces—often system fonts like SF Pro Display on macOS—that prioritize legibility over personality. The font size defaults to 16-18px, with line-height set to approximately 1.6-1.7, providing ample breathing room for the text. This is humanist typography: warm, open, and designed to serve the reader's eyes, not to make a design statement.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Minimal Interface, Maximum Focus</h3>
            <p>
                The application's interface vanishes during use. Menus collapse, toolbars hide, and the entire experience reduces to text on a screen. This minimalism is not coldness—it's warmth expressed through absence. By removing geometric decorations and aggressive UI elements, iA Writer honors the user's cognitive resources and respects their time.
            </p>
            
            <p>
                <strong>HM Principle Demonstrated:</strong> Content-first layout prioritizes the reading experience with optimal line measure, generous typography, and clear hierarchy over decorative complexity.
            </p>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
        <article class="example-article">
            <h2 class="example-title">Medium.com: The Reading Experience Refined</h2>
            
            <blockquote class="example-quote">
                <p>"We believe the best ideas deserve the best presentation. Reading should be a pleasure, not a chore."</p>
                <footer>— Medium Design Team</footer>
            </blockquote>
            
            <figure class="example-figure">
                <img src="{{ '/images/examples/medium-article-layout.jpg' | baseUrl }}"
                     alt="Screenshot of Medium's homepage with large, serif headlines and warm, muted background colors."
                     loading="lazy"
                     class="example-screenshot">
                <figcaption class="image-caption">Visual: Medium's use of generous, humanist typography and warm, accessible colors establishes immediate reading comfort.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            
            <p>
                Medium's design philosophy represents a watershed moment in Humanist Modernism on the web. While it has evolved over the years, its core commitment remains unwavering: optimize every design decision around the reading experience.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Generous Typography</h3>
            <p>
                Medium's default body text size is 18-21px—directly aligned with Humanist Modernism's prescription. The line-height exceeds 1.7, often reaching 1.75 or higher, creating the "breathing room" that Edward Tufte advocated for in information design. These decisions are not aesthetic flourishes; they are foundational commitments to reader comfort.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Paragraph Spacing & Visual Rhythm</h3>
            <p>
                Between paragraphs, Medium employs generous vertical spacing—often 1.5em or more. This spacing accomplishes multiple goals: it prevents visual fatigue, creates natural stopping points for readers to absorb ideas, and establishes a calm, unhurried reading pace. The generous spacing reflects an underlying humanist philosophy: the reader's cognitive experience matters more than fitting more content on the screen.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Color & Contrast</h3>
            <p>
                Medium uses warm, neutral colors—typically dark gray text (#2c2c2c or similar) on near-white backgrounds (#f9f9f9). This color palette, influenced by humanist design principles, reduces eye strain and creates a warm, inviting reading environment. Links use muted, warm accent colors rather than jarring primary colors, maintaining visual harmony while remaining functional.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Content-Centered Layout</h3>
            <p>
                The article width is constrained to approximately 700-760px, ensuring no single line exceeds optimal reading length. This constraint is enforced across all devices, with responsive behavior that maintains readability on mobile and desktop alike. The layout serves the content, not the screen.
            </p>
            
            <p>
                <strong>HM Principle Demonstrated:</strong> Empathetic typography and generous spacing prioritize the reader's comfort, using humanist sans-serifs with open apertures and variable stroke width to create warmth and legibility.
            </p>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

