        <article class="example-article">
            <h2 class="example-title">Edward Tufte's Data Visualization: Information as Clarity</h2>
            
            <blockquote class="example-quote">
                <p>"The highest density of truth per square inch. Excellence is the common denominator of all things related to information design."</p>
                <footer>— Edward Tufte, Visual Display of Quantitative Information</footer>
            </blockquote>
            
            <figure class="example-figure">
                <img src="{{ '/images/examples/tufte-dataink.jpg' | baseUrl }}"
                     alt="Diagram listing Tufte's principles, including 'Minimize Chartjunk' and 'Maximize Data-Ink Ratio.'"
                     loading="lazy"
                     class="example-screenshot">
                <figcaption class="image-caption">Conceptual: This image's principles are foundational to HM, specifically the elimination of unnecessary decoration (Chartjunk) in favor of clarity.</figcaption>
            </figure>
            
            <p>
                While Edward Tufte is not a digital product designer, his work on information visualization forms the philosophical foundation of Humanist Modernism's approach to design. His principles of data-ink ratio, chartjunk elimination, and reader-centric clarity directly influence how HM practitioners approach digital interfaces.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Maximizing Data-Ink Ratio</h3>
            <p>
                Tufte's concept of the "data-ink ratio" asserts that every pixel should serve a purpose: conveying information to the reader. Decorative elements—drop shadows, gradients, 3D effects, geometric abstraction—are eliminated ruthlessly. In Humanist Modernism, this principle extends beyond data visualization to entire interfaces: every visual element must earn its place by serving the user's understanding.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Eliminating Chartjunk</h3>
            <p>
                Tufte's famous attack on "chartjunk"—unnecessary decorations that obscure data—parallels Humanist Modernism's rejection of Bauhaus geometric ornament. A bar chart decorated with triangles and circles is not more beautiful; it is actively harmful to comprehension. Similarly, a navigation menu decorated with geometric shapes distracts from its primary function: helping users find information.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Respecting the Reader's Intelligence</h3>
            <p>
                Tufte's work is fundamentally humanist because it assumes readers are intelligent and capable of absorbing complex information when it is presented clearly. There is no "dumbing down" of content, no oversimplification, no patronizing explanations. Instead, Tufte advocates for dense, information-rich presentations that trust the reader's ability to engage deeply. This respect for the reader is at the heart of Humanist Modernism.
            </p>
            
            <h3 class="example-subtitle">Typography in Service of Clarity</h3>
            <p>
                In his books and presentations, Tufte uses generous margins, ample whitespace, and carefully selected typefaces to maximize comprehension. His layouts are not minimal in the Bauhaus sense (geometric, spare) but humanist in their approach: every element of typography, spacing, and layout exists to serve the reader's understanding and comfort.
            </p>
            
            <p>
                <strong>HM Principle Demonstrated:</strong> Readability paramount—legibility as the cornerstone, with generous body text, ample line-height, and clear hierarchy serving the reader first and foremost.
            </p>
        </article>
    </div>
