        <div class="example-summary">
            <h2 class="example-summary-title">Common Threads</h2>
            
            <p>
                These three canonical examples—iA Writer, Medium, and Edward Tufte's work—share fundamental commitments that define Humanist Modernism:
            </p>
            
            <ul class="example-principles">
                <li>
                    <strong>Content First:</strong> Design decisions are made in service of content clarity and reader comfort, not aesthetic novelty.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Generous Typography:</strong> Body text sizes exceed 16px, line-heights exceed 1.6, and letter-spacing is open and natural. The reader's eyes matter.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Optimal Reading Measure:</strong> Line length is constrained to 65-80 characters, respecting cognitive and visual limits of human reading.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Warmth Over Coldness:</strong> Colors are warm neutrals and earth tones. Interfaces feel human-scaled and approachable, not mechanical or austere.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Elimination of Ornament:</strong> Geometric decorations, aggressive animations, and visual noise are removed. What remains serves a purpose.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Respect for Intelligence:</strong> Designs trust the reader's ability to understand complex information. Clarity is achieved through organization and typography, not simplification.
                </li>
            </ul>
            
            <p>
                These examples demonstrate that Humanist Modernism is not a historical aesthetic to be revived, but a living, evolving philosophy that continues to shape digital design today. When we prioritize the reader over the designer, clarity over novelty, and human comfort over geometric abstraction, we create designs that endure.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
